metadata.name: Asterium #287
metadata.description:
Asterium is a token that will grow with you, for an entire year. Changing and morphing over time to eventually reach its equilibrium.

It is a token where I try to symbolize the journey of life.
Where looking back is the best way to look forward.
Where looking into the future is not a possibility.
Where each day is as uncertain as the next.

A token that will surprise you and have its ups and downs as it grows over time.



Pricing:
Dutch auction 64-16-8, where anybody that picks one up at 64 tez gets a print of how their galaxy looks on any day from the present to day 0. Meaning you can claim the print at any point in the future.

The print will be printed on high quality hahnemühle torchon paper at 30x40 cm (11.81 x 15.75 in). Printed at a local print shop here in Utrecht. This paper has a rough texture to it that matches the textures of space perfectly.



Usage:
- Hover over your Asterium to view the name, date, days passed, status and render stats.
- Double press to export the current frame as a .png image.
- Use the slider at the bottom to scroll back in time to the days before today, you can go as far back as day 0 and as far forwards as today.
- The token refreshes every hour, so framing it in a digital picture frame is totally possible!

metadata.name: Levitation #197
metadata.description:
Abstract structures floating in space. 

——————

Levitation continues my exploration of Suprematism and Geometric Abstraction. It contains my developments and ideas for the past half a year.
Starting as mostly inspired by Kleine Welten (Small Worlds) series by Wassily Kandinsky, the collection evolved more into Suprematic compositions.

——————

To change the size of an image, open it in live view and add ‘&size=[size (6200 max.)]’ to the end of the URL.

Controls:
[Arrow Up / Down] — increase / decrease animation speed.
[R] — skip the animation.
[C] — switch between clean and grainy versions.
[S] — save the image.

Created using p5.js and GLSL.
License: CC BY-NC-SA 4.0.

——————

hrunz. — Nov. 2022.

metadata.name: Fictional Cityscapes #48
metadata.description:
Some of the most stunning, and beloved, images are large cities, viewed from afar at the right angle, and preferably with some water in front. 

This project comes from my experiments with line art, and is slightly inspired by Hevey's amazing Dencity drop, which is on a different level to most generative art. 

The cities here are based on some fictional tower architecture and some unusual skies.

metadata.name: Chop Chop #174
metadata.description:
Chop Chop is a complementary collection to Caterpillars that I prepared to thank my collectors for the amazing love and interest you showed to my work. I did not want to force my way to your wallets with unsolicited thank-you nfts, so all holders of Caterpillars will have a reserve spot to mint at least 1 tokens per wallet for 0 tez ( I dont understand the reserve options fully, sorry - 128 editions reserved for holders of Caterpillars) . 

The holders of this collection will have reserve spots for my next  collection. The reserve spots will be held for one week from minting, and I prefer the unreserved editions to be fair game for anyone, so first come, first served.

I decided to re-work this older project of mine because it was going to take some time for me to prepare an independent and novel collection and also wanted to continue learning new things. The concept is Paul Klee meets Vector Math and Flow Fields, as you can see the visuals are heavily inspired by Paul Klee's work :)

Under the hood, the circles and triangles act as repulsive forces that break and distort the grid, and push the squares in their range out of their way, forming some holes in the fabric created by the same algo that made Caterpillars. 

I have only added one rarity feature which is the palette because this one uses almost all the palettes from Caterpillars (minus neon dreams). I am hoping that this project will not be about rarity, but more like a thank-you gift and an easy way to access my future work.

Well, I hope you will like it...

- Press "s" to save a png.

- Also, 33% royalty split wth the Processing Foundation, % 33 with the minters (if there will be any secondary sales) 

DISCLAIMER :
I am very very new to coding and not very good at this. I have tried to clean up the code as best as I could, and I hope that there is nothing terribly wrong left inside.

metadata.name: How Stars Really Look #40
metadata.description:
When I was a kid, I used to draw stars as circles, while my friends drew them as 5-pointed "regular" stars. I used to think they were wrong.

But when I grew up and saw a real star very closely, I realized that it was I who was wrong.

In "How Stars Really Look", I present to you a hundred images of real stars, which are billions of lightyears away from us, and which cannot be seen by eyes or by any device.

* * *

This is my 1st "Thank You" project to show my gratitude to the fxhash community for supporting me and collecting my previous generative art projects. THANK YOU!! 💜

Press S to save as PNG.

Made by: yenren / twitter.com/yenrenART
Made with: JavaScript + HTML Canvas
License: LICENSE.txt

metadata.name: Penumbra #31
metadata.description:
Penumbra is a geometric exploration of the possible outcomes from 3 basic rules:

1) Place some walls
2) Place some light sources
3) Draw the resulting shadows

This series is a small thank you to the collectors of Umbra :)

metadata.name: Shoji #129
metadata.description:
A shoji is a traditional Japanese screen, consisting of translucent sheets on a lattice frame. 

This work used two shoji-inspired lattices, overlayed so they form a composite pattern. The geometry of each lattice is then manipulated to produce organic curves and playful interactions between the layers. 

This is an animated loop, but can be paused as required.

:: Shortcut keys ::
Space - pause/play the animation
S - save a PNG image at 4000 x 4000 px

- - - - - 

Made with code and love by AutoEclectus.

 AutoEclectus is a visual artist specialising in code-based generative works.
